%FEATURE_STRUCTURES.sofaString: Patient 2 is the older brother of Patient 1. He was recognized to have similar craniofacial features during childhood but without craniosynostosis (Figure 1). Head shape at age 8 years at time of referral to a craniofacial clinic was described as brachycephaly with retrusion of supraorbital rims and proptosis. Maxilla was retruded with Class III malocclusion. Submerged deciduous teeth were documented at age 12â€‰years. He had bilateral chronic serious otitis media with conductive hearing loss. At age 7 years, agenesis of the right malleus and incus and fixation of the right stapes was noted at the time of surgical middle ear exploration. Otoscopy at age 13â€‰years suggested absence of the left incus with continued serous effusion. He was treated with orthodontics and a combination of LeFort I and LeFort III maxillary osteotomy with distraction and iliac crest bone graft. As an adult, he was seen for medical genetics evaluation at another center where his height was 188â€‰cm and weight 72.5 kg. No OFC was documented. His craniofacies, hands and feet were described as normal. Intelligence is normal. He has developed a seizure disorder. Magnetic resonance imaging (MRI) of the brain and cervical spine showed mild Chiari 1 malformation with a small syrinx at C2.
